# Keep the OS map current

The `/dev/os-map` page (also `/dashboard`) is an interactive, Railway-style
canvas meant to be a true visual of the project's guts and workflow. When you
add, remove, or significantly change a feature, service, API route, external
integration, or Telegram bot command, update the map **in the same change**.

Single source of truth: **`public/dev/os-map-data.js`**

The page is **tabbed** via `MAPS` in that file. Each map is
`{ id, title, nodes, edges, groups }`:

- **`system`** — the runtime architecture (clients, Reave App, external APIs).
- **`tooling`** — the "MCP & CLI" dev plane (Cursor agent → MCP servers / CLIs →
  platforms → production). Update it when an MCP server or CLI is added/removed
  or when what a tool can reach changes.

Within each map:

- `nodes` — services / integrations / clients (id, title, sub, icon, brand, hue, status, ghost, group, x, y).
  - `brand` is a [Simple Icons](https://simpleicons.org) slug (e.g. `railway`,
    `github`, `supabase`). When set, the card shows the company's real logo
    (tinted to the node hue); `icon` (an emoji) stays as the fallback for brands
    Simple Icons doesn't carry (Twilio, BrowserStack) or generic nodes. Confirm a
    slug exists before using it.
- `edges` — connections (from, to, label, dashed, ghost).
- `groups` — Railway-project-style containers (id, title, hue, members).

Give each node a distinct `hue` (0–360) so the map stays full-spectrum (in the
`tooling` map a vendor may share its hue across its mcp/cli/svc nodes on
purpose). The render/interaction engine is `public/dev/os-map-loader.js` (tabs,
drag + snap, pan, zoom, per-map persistence) — only touch it for behavior
changes, not content.
